			<h1 style="text-align: center">Part II</h1>
			<h2 style="text-align: center">World Generation</h2>
			<p><span style="font-family: 'Glass Antiqua', cursive; font-size: 48px;">D</span>warf Fortress could probably be a useful tool for real-life geologists.  Not everything is a perfect match, but the level of detail is astounding (and this theme echoes across the entire game).</p>
			<p><strong>Create New World</strong> (without advanced parameters) is straightforward, and you can do some light customization.  The advanced option gives you LOTS of room to mess things up, I’ll skip this for now.</p>
			<p><strong>World Size</strong> is the size of the total map and all its civilizations and histories.  I use small maps.  Large maps can take a VERY long time to generate, especially with a lot of…</p>
		</div><!--cont_left-->
        <div id="cont_right">
			<p><strong>History</strong> is how long the world exists before your party strikes off to build a fort.  I usually keep this SHORT in order to speed up world gen times and because I don’t want to risk a race dying out, which can happen!  Short history.</p>
			<p>Civs, sites, beasts, and savagery I leave default.  They are pretty self explanatory. </p> 
			<p><strong>Minerals</strong>, however, I bump up one notch, because I like having metal.  Keep in mind that this variable can affect flat lands and water supply such as rivers and brooks.</p>
			<p>If you change generation variables too much, you will get “failed” world gen attempts.  Sometimes a few of these will happen even if you go default, but very odd worlds will see many failed attempts.</p>
			<p>Hit “y” to generate a map!  You can scroll around a bit to see if you’d like to keep it, but details will be hidden until you’re ready to embark.  All maps will have a cold end and a hot end, the poles can be reversed however so north is not always hot, and south is not always the cold end. </p> 
			<p style="padding: 0; margin: 0;"><a href="images/tut_img/worldgen.jpg" rel="lightbox" alt="World Generation"><img src="images/tut_img/worldgen.jpg" class="right" width="35%"/></a>Generate a world you like and “a”ccept it, then you’re ready to begin looking for a place to build your fort!  Start playing in your world and we’re off.</p>
